<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Austrian coalition set to hold power but right gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austria's long-ruling coalition of conservatives and socialists, led by
Chancellor Franz Vranitzky, looked set to return to power after yesterday's
national elections, but with a much reduced 63 per cent of the vote, down
from 75 per cent in 1990.
Voters deserted the Social Democratic party and the conservative Austrian
People's party (OVP) in large numbers for both right and leftwing fringe
parties, raising the prospect of a significant realignment soon.
The biggest winner was the charismatic Jorg Haider, leader of the far right
Freedom party. The FPO raised its share from 16 per cent to nearly 23 per
cent, and could theoretically form a conservative coalition with the OVP.
However, both Mr Haider and Mr Erhard Busek, OVP leader, have ruled this
out, and Mr Vranitzky and Mr Busek said last night they aimed to renew their
pact.
Mr Haider, who came to international attention with a complimentary comment
three years ago about the employment policies of Hitler's Third Reich said
he expected to lead the government after the next election.
Adversaries do not accuse him of being a neo-Nazi, but he appealed openly
during the campaign to voters' xenophobic tendencies, blaming immigrants for
rising crime rates and accusing the government of treating them too
generously.
The coalition's poor result means it will have only 118 of parliament's 183
seats, down from 140. It will no longer have the two-thirds of seats needed
for constitutional changes but can count on the support of the Liberal
Forum, a new left-leaning party which won 5.7 per cent and 10 seats, for the
vote to ratify European Union entry.
The Greens, who raised their seat count from 10 to 13, have been divided on
EU entry. Mr Haider opposed it vigorously, but in vain, in the referendum
campaign four months ago.
The coalition's lost support was blamed mainly on disenchantment with the
cosy partnership between the socialists and conservatives that has governed
since the second world war.
Mr Haider was particularly effective during the campaign at rooting out
examples of excessive patronage given to friends of the ruling parties. Last
night he said the result was a sign 'we have finally succeeded in putting
post-war Austria behind us and ushering in a genuine democracy'.
The OVP's vote has been eroding since the mid-1980s. In this poll its share
dropped from 32.1 per cent to 27.7 per cent for 52 seats, eight fewer.
However, for the first time, the socialists were hurt, their share plunging
from 42.8 per cent to 35 per cent and their seats falling from 80 to 66.
</TEXT>
