<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Observer: Penny wise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative central office's efforts to reduce its estimated Pounds 15m
overdraft will not be helped by gaffes such as the one visited on Sir
Alistair Grant, the genial Scottish millionaire who is chairman of the
Argyll supermarket group.
Sir Alistair, whose company has over the past decade contributed some Pounds
250,000 to Tory coffers, was irritated earlier this year to receive a
gushing letter from party HQ asking him to consider making a 'first time'
donation.
As an indication of the party's organisational prowess, Sir Alistair
considered this less than impressive. He promptly cut the company's annual
donation from Pounds 30,000 to zero.
Who carries the can for the embarrassing error? Central office is
understandably reticent but it is reliably understood the letter was
authorised by David Sieff, the Marks and Spencer director, and until
recently among the high-powered businessmen helping to run the Tories'
finances.
For entirely unconnected reasons, Sieff is now devoting his spare time to
being chairman of the board distributing cash from the UK's new national
lottery.
