<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / FT guide to corruption in France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
France has been hit this year by a wave of high-profile corruption
investigations. Who has been affected, and how high have the investigations
reached?
The striking feature of the corruption investigations is that they have
involved some of France's leading businessmen and senior politicians. So far
this year, one cabinet minister, Alain Carignon, the communications
minister, has resigned following a corruption probe. Gerard Longuet, the
industry minister, faces pressure to resign following an investigation into
payments for his holiday home in Saint Tropez. And colleagues from his
Republican Party have been cited in probes concerning illicit political
funding. The chairmen of some of France's leading companies, including Saint
Gobain, Alcatel Alsthom and Schneider, have also been placed under
investigation in cases involving alleged fraud or influence peddling.
Why has there been such a surge in corruption cases?
These investigations are not new in France. In the 1980s, for example, the
Socialist party found itself the target of investigations, following the
discovery of Urba, a national network of bogus consultancies which
channelled money from business contractors to the party's coffers. But the
snaring of senior figures reflects a more aggressive approach by France's
investigating magistrates, who have been influenced, according to some
observers, by the experience of Italy's corruption-hunting judges. At the
same time, the decentralisation of decision-making to the provinces over the
past decade has increased opportunities for corruption.
Is corruption widespread? Is France like Italy?
Prime minister Edouard Balladur firmly rejects the comparison. 'Corruption
in France is nothing like the situation in Italy', he said earlier this
month, arguing that the spree of investigations reflected the increased
freedom of the judiciary to pursue cases which largely date back to the
1980s. He is probably right to dismiss the parallel. But the extent of the
problem in France does appear significant. A poll by Le Monde last month
found that two out of three French company chairmen suspect that illegal
practices are common in the business world, while a study by Le Nouvel
Observateur, the weekly magazine, claims there are more than 60 ongoing
corruption investigations into businessmen and politicians.
Is there a common thread to the various probes?
Often, yes. The investigations into Saint Gobain, Cogedim, the property
developer, and utilities companies all involve alleged links to a
politician, a political party or a public contract. The cases often involve
accusations that contracts were awarded in return for political funds. The
investigation into Carignon, for example, includes allegations that a
utilities company bailed out a publishing group which supported his
electoral campaigns in return for a water supply contract in Grenoble.
Alcatel and Schneider are different. In the former case, the chairman is
accused of using company funds for building work at his private properties.
In the latter, a Belgian magistrate claims that the chairman short-changed
minority shareholders in the group's Belgian subsidiaries through a series
of offshore companies.
What are the political implications? Does the spate of investigations
represent a threat to the government?
The various cases represent a growing dilemma for the prime minister.
Balladur's presidential ambitions depend partly on the support of Longuet
and his Republican Party, the biggest element in the UDF, the junior partner
in the ruling coalition. Should Longuet be forced to resign, and should his
party be dragged more deeply into corruption investigations, the prime
minister would be deprived of a potentially important ally in his bid for
the conservative candidacy in the presidential poll. More broadly, the fact
that the political right is now in the firing line could damage its standing
with voters, in the same way that a perception of corruption contributed to
the Socialist party's heavy defeat in last year's general elections.
How is the government responding, and what reforms are necessary to resolve
the problem?
Balladur's initial response was to let the investigations work their course.
But he has come under increasing pressure to take further action and is now
proposing an annual audit of the personal assets of ministers, MPs and
senior local officials. Several influential politicians, including Pierre
Mehaignerie, the justice minister, have raised the prospect of a complete
ban on corporate funding for political parties, thereby extending
legislation of 1988 and 1990, which set limits on contributions and limited
spending by candidates in elections. The two principal options are: to
establish a system in which the French state picks up the tab for the
country's politicking, with a direct and controlled system of financing for
political parties; or to introduce a buffer between individual companies and
politicians through the creation of foundations to receive general corporate
donations, as happens in Germany.
</TEXT>
<XX>
