<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Sport: Life after the Olympic ring cycle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Olympic gold medals are tricky. Or rather, life after a gold medal can be
tricky. Like an Oxbridge degree, gold medals open doors. But what happens
next depends to a large degree on the ability of the athlete to translate
commitment and drive into new fields, yet retain the humility of a beginner.
Many believe they can walk on water - and promptly sink. 'In the outside
world it's important to recognise your own limitations. Sports people are
very bad at that,' says Chris Boardman, the young and virtually unknown
British track cyclist who won a gold medal two years ago at the Barcelona
Olympics. 'That's because, when you're competing, it's essential to believe
you can do anything.'
During their event, Olympic champions admit no doubts. But Boardman's career
may have entered a new phase on Saturday with the inaugural meeting at
Britain's new Pounds 9m velodrome in Manchester, where he triumphed over
Francis Moreau of France in a fascinating re-match with the man he beat in
Sicily recently to become world 4,000 metres pursuit champion.
In the afternoon's other crowd-pleaser, Yvonne McGregor, winner of Britain's
only cycling gold at this year's Commonwealth Games, was beaten by world
pursuit champion Marion Clignet.
Although the fact was well-disguised from the public, neither event would
have happened without the involvement of Boardman wearing, for the first
time, a promoter's hat. Five weeks ago the original promoters withdrew from
the meeting. As this is Britain's first-ever purpose-built, indoor cycling
stadium, it may be safe to assume that Britain's market for indoor sprint
events is relatively untested.
Many people have warned the British Cycling Federation, which is now based
in the vast Manchester stadium and will pay its considerable operating
costs, that it may have been handed a poisoned chalice. What is certain is
that an inaugural event without stars, consisting of largely unknown amateur
riders in national teams, would have given the velodrome a send-off to match
that of the Titanic.
'Chris would have ridden in the English team, but to be honest it might have
seemed a bit like Linford Christie jogging in the park on a Sunday,' said
Peter Woodworth, who is Boardman's business mentor and co-director of Beyond
Level Four, the company they established to maximise Boardman's potential.
'I brought Francis and the two girls here to add a bit of sparkle to what
should be a very special event for British cycling,' says Boardman, 26. 'It
sounds corny but it is a chance to put something back into the sport.
However, once I started to be involved in doing this, I began to think that
in time my company could have a future in sports promotion.'
After his Barcelona triumph - riding that futuristic carbon-fibre bicycle
built by Lotus - the popular media made much of Boardman's status as an
unemployed cabinet-maker launched into sports fame. Is it not an even bigger
step in just two years from dole queue to becoming the Mr Fixit of Europe's
velodromes?
'The dole business was a myth with some truth in it,' says Boardman, who
possesses a remarkably analytical mind. 'I had decided to give up my job in
order to invest the time in training to be an international sportsman.'
That decision paid off, but others lay ahead. 'When they hang it around your
neck, you know your gold medal has the potential to give you security for
life, but it all depends on how you use it. It's a desperately big
responsibility. At the start I avoided making any decisions because I was
too afraid of making a mistake.'
Ironically, among Boardman's priorities was to remain an amateur. 'It's a
horrendously hard life as a professional cyclist and I wanted to stay in my
comfy niche,' he says.
However, Peter Woodworth, an ex-cyclist from the same Merseyside club as
Boardman (although a generation older) and a businessman, persuaded the gold
medallist that he could not stand still in the relatively tiny world of
amateur sprint cycling.
Last season Boardman made his Tour de France debut in the prestigious Gan
team. Wearing the legendary maillot jeune (yellow jersey) after the first
stage was the stuff of fantasy, yet it happened. Although he stopped short
of the mountain stages, Gan were impressed enough with the newcomer to plan
next season's road-racing team around the Englishman.
Rumours that Boardman is now earning the Pounds 1m a year paid to retired
team-leader Greg LeMond are laughed off. But Woodworth agrees that next year
his protege will be the best-paid second-year professional on the Tour.
Boardman says he is financially on target to retire when he is 32 - but
won't, because he is a happily self-diagnosed workaholic.
My final question had to be about that name. Beyond Level Four? It sounds
like something from the further reaches of software engineering, or a San
Francisco PR company. It emerges that Boardman has for years prepared for
races on a unique four-level training regime. The first level is a simple
'recovery ride', the fourth 'a period of maximal intensity'.
'The name means a lot to us,' he said. 'We don't yet know what's beyond
Level Four.' And then he laughed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
