<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cracker (Monday, 9-10pm, ITV) returns for an encore which is shorter than
ITV would have liked. Writer Jimmy McGovern has decided to restrict himself
to half the number of episodes Granada wanted to commission.
Robbie Coltrane fizzes as Fitz the hard-drinking, big-gambling forensic
psychologist who, in the first episode, gets to grips with a bereaved father
seeking revenge for his son, who died in the Hillsborough tragedy.
An absorbing documentary on Porton Down in Network First (Tuesday,
10.40-11.40pm, ITV) details Porton's leading role in developing chemical
weapons since the start of this century. Porton Down also appears to have
benefitted from data collected by Nazis in the concentration camps.
The programme-makers have unearthed evidence of experiments performed on
human volunteers which have left them riddled with disease and, in one case,
dead. Many of the British volunteers have suffered quietly for years, having
been sworn to silence by the Official Secrets Act.
However, Porton Down's US counterpart has started paying compensation to its
human guinea pigs, which has resulted in a trickle of information that the
documentary traces to its source with astonishing results.
Jazz fans should tune in for Alan Plater's Screen One: Doggin' Around
(Sunday, 10.05-11.35pm, BBC1), with Ronnie Scott playing himself, Elliott
Gould as a has-been pianist and Geraldine James as his minder. It combines
Plater's two obsessions - jazz and the north of England - and he has a lot
of fun with in-jokes, some of them so obtuse that only aficionados will get
them all.
</TEXT>
