<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / NHS trusts will be told to reveal costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, will next week tell National
Health Service trusts to give more information about the amount they spend
on management.
Amid growing concern that trust hospitals and community health groups spend
too much on bureaucracy, she will tell trust chief executives to give full
details of management costs in their annual accounts with effect from April
next year.
At the Conservative party conference this week she will announce that the
government may issue league tables of management spending by trusts in order
to expose those that spend too much.
A senior Department of Health official said last week: 'The government is
determined to pile the pressure on the trusts.
'The message will be that there is no hiding place for bureaucracy, and that
you have to be open and accountable about what you spend.'
The assault on management costs follows a strong attack on bureaucracy in
the health service by Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, at his party's
Blackpool conference last week. Mr Blair said that the NHS reforms had
benefited 'not the patient but the penpusher'.
Concern about the issue has also been felt in the government. There are
indications that the number of NHS managers rose by nearly 25 per cent in
1992.
Mrs Bottomley will remind Tory delegates this week that she is committed to
reducing NHS bureaucracy by axing the regional health authorities in England
and paving the way for mergers of district health authorities and family
health service authorities.
But in recent months health department officials have completed the initial
groundwork for introducing league tables of management spending by trust
hospitals.
In July a confidential report into spending by trusts was completed by
Whitehall officials, the Trust Federation and the Audit Commision, the
government spending watchdog. The report defines what an NHS manager is. The
government is concerned that Labour MPs, unions and other critics have used
a definition that includes medical practitioners.
The report found that NHS trusts spent an average of about 6.5 per cent of
their budgets on management, a figure the health department could use as a
guide to how much should be spent in future.
Health department officials made clear last week that the government does
not have statutory powers to set a limit on management spending or to force
trusts to account for it. But they were confident that Mrs Bottomley's call
for management costs to be made explicit in annual accounts would be heeded.
</TEXT>
