<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Rise in interest rates hits public optimism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last month's rise in interest rates sharply reversed a rise in public
optimism about employment prospects and the economy, says the latest FT/MFS
Mood of the Nation index.
The index has fallen from 91 in early August to 83 at the end of September,
the lowest figure since the spring. Professor Robert Worcester, chairman of
MORI Financial Services, the index compiler, said: 'What is worse for the
government, the beneficiaries of the interest rate rise do not register any
increase in approval, while those who are hit by it register strong
disapproval.'
The 24 per cent of householders who own their homes outright, and who are
more likely to be net savers, registered an index figure for their mood of
125, the same as in August.
Mortgage holders, who make up 44 per cent of householders, registered a
decline from 86 to 80, and council tenants, who make up 22 per cent of
householders, from 80 to 71.
The mood - judged by three questions on well-being and employment security -
started at 100 in April 1993. It fell sharply until March, since when it
recovered to a peak of 91 at the beginning of August.
The most recent fall in optimism is much stronger among women than men and
is much stronger in the 25 to 34 age group than among the old.
Like other surveys, the Mood of the Nation index suggests that fear of
redundancy remains high in spite of the fall in registered unemployment. The
unemployment index remained at 7 per cent, as it has in the past 12 months.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Economic Indicators.
