<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Sainsbury joins supermarket price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J. Sainsbury is joining the autumn price skirmishing with rival supermarket
groups with a series of bold, 10-second TV advertisements offering a third
or more off the price of selected products.
The UK's biggest food retailer said the brash campaign - a departure from
its celebrity recipe advertisements - was designed to improve perceptions of
its pricing, alongside its reputation for quality.
The campaign started yesterday as Iceland, the frozen food retailer,
launched an 'Everyday super value range' of basic frozen goods which it said
were being sold at almost 20 per cent below their 1984 prices.
Sainsbury's new advertisements, more reminiscent of a discount chain but
carrying its long-standing slogan 'Sainsbury's - where good food costs
less', will run in tandem with its recipe advertisements, producing what Mr
Ivor Hunt, marketing director, called a 'double whammy'.
Mr Hunt said that in addition to its strong brand name Sainsbury's weekly
price check on 750 product lines consistently showed it had a 2 per cent or
3 per cent price advantage over competitors.
He said: 'We want to strengthen our price perception. We don't get the
credit for these low prices.' He added that the group was using 'short,
dramatic and to-the-point' advertisements to 'illustrate prices in a
stronger way'.
Mr Hunt denied that the advertisements might be seen as downmarket or risk
harming the Sainsbury's brand.
The advertisements will be backed by a programme of other temporary price
cuts. Mr Hunt expected reduced gross margins to be 'more than offset' by
increased sales.
Sainsbury is also continuing its 'Essentials' campaign, launched a year ago,
offering indefinite reductions an about 300 products.
Autumn promotions are an established feature of food retailing, but the
aggressiveness of this year's campaigns reflects the highly competitive
environment, with superstore groups squeezed by slow spending growth, a
low-inflation environment, competition from cut-price chains, and increasing
market saturation.
</TEXT>
