<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Companies found to be worse off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturing companies appear to be in a worse position, with lower wage
productivity and profits and higher borrowings, than they were before the
volatile business environment of the late 1980s, according to a report on
medium-sized businesses in the Yorkshire area, Humberside and the north of
England.
Because profits in the late 1980s were used to reduce long-term debts,
increase wages and invest, subsequent decline in demand has left survivors
in many sectors with excess capacity and, in spite of considerable
redundancies, a less efficient workforce, it says.
The manufacturing sector has also suffered from increased competition from
abroad and the emergence of cheaper imported goods. Many companies face a
difficult path back to the high levels of profit, investment and employment
enjoyed during the 1980s.
It says medium-sized companies are an important vehicle for future economic
growth, particularly in the Yorkshire area and Humberside. But essential
pre-requisites to their success include wide-ranging skills, a global
outlook, constant investment in the development of people and the harnessing
of new technologies.
'Medium-sized businesses are substantial enough and flexible enough to meet
this challenge, but have a poor economic foundation to build on,' says the
report. It concludes that a 'developmental' stance needs be taken by
investors, government economic policy and the businesses themselves to
realise potential.
Profitability Trends in Northern Industries. Marketing Department, Lloyds
Bowmaker Ltd, Corporate Finance Division, Finance House, 51 Holdenhurst Rd,
Bournemouth BH8 8EP. Free.
</TEXT>
