<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Employee survey results kept secret
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies which use workforce surveys to obtain information from their
employees are often reluctant to share all their findings with their staff,
a report says today.
The increasing popularity of surveys was reflected in the high degree of
satisfaction with results reported among the Industrial Society study of 264
organisations which have carried out recent surveys. Three-quarters of those
questioned said they would repeat the employee survey in the next two years.
The society said employee communications, health and safety, and training
were the topics most frequently investigated in the surveys, which cost
Pounds 10,000 each on average. In most cases, it said, managers would
produce post-survey action plans, although only half of the managers
canvassed thought their plans were proving successful.
The average response rate among employees was 66 per cent, said the report.
The study coincides with a critical report on employee surveys by
International Survey Research, a surveying organisation. The report said
some employers were using surveys wrongly - introducing them when they were
unnecessary, surveying too frequently, spreading them too wide and using
poor survey instruments.
</TEXT>
