shows demand for temporary staff at its 200 branches at its highest since
1989. Demand for permanent staff is slightly above half the level of 1990.
Reed suggested that the growth in the use of temporary staff could reflect a
structural change in the composition of the UK workforce or the slow rate of
upturn leading employers to postpone decisions on the conversion of
temporary posts to full-time jobs.
