<DATE>941010
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / Banks 'ease lending criteria to win business'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Banks are slackening their lending criteria, reducing margins and attempting
'imprudent' rates of lending growth in response to UK companies seeking
finance from other sources, says the latest annual survey from the
Association of Corporate Treasurers and the Bank Relationship Consultancy.
It says the fall in margins on syndicated loans to the biggest companies in
the past year - a trend which is increasingly worrying bankers - is also
occurring in private loans to large and medium-sized companies.
The survey of 139 banks and 233 companies finds that companies are seeking
alternative funding as business confidence grows.
Banks are allowing looser loan criteria in an effort to persuade companies
to borrow from them.
It also finds that banks are increasingly willing to lend for up to 10
years, rather than restricting loans to two or three years, as in the past.
More banks want to lend in larger amounts of between Pounds 20m and Pounds
50m.
Companies say they are willing to pay slightly higher margins on loans in
order to reduce the number of criteria. They are also willing to pay more to
ensure that banks do not have the right to sell their loan to others.
The survey says that although companies want to increase borrowing from
banks, they intend to seek more funding from other sources such as private
placement of debt in the US, leasing, and issuing sterling bonds.
It says these trends are no longer confined to the largest companies with
high credit ratings. In response, banks are becoming more willing to lend to
unquoted companies and those with lower ratings.
Mr Alastair Winter of the Bank Relationship Consultancy said commercial-bank
lending was being restricted by the growing ability of investment banks to
bridge the gap between investors and companies.
The survey says 70 per cent of banks plan substantial lending growth, with
three-quarters of those seeking growth of more than 5 per cent. It is often
thought risky for banks to expand their loans faster than the company is
growing.
Although banks say that they have to gain other forms of business from big
companies to make up for low returns on lending, the survey found that few
banks have minimum requirements for returns from borrowers.
Banks have also made only limited efforts to build up strong relationships
with companies. More than 60 per cent of them allocated 10 or more accounts
to each lending manager, and changed managers more frequently than every
three years.
The UK Corporate Banking Market 1994. Bank Relationship Consultancy, 2-8
Victoria Avenue, London EC2M 4NS. Pounds 550.
</TEXT>
