<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 94 / US warns Saddam of 'horrendous' price for war: Kuwait sends
troops to Iraqi border - 2,000 marines arrive in Gulf
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and ROBIN ALLEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO, KUWAIT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US stepped up deployment of a 'formidable force' of troops, warships and
jets in the Gulf yesterday and warned Iraq it would pay an 'horrendous
price' if President Saddam Hussein ordered an invasion of Kuwait.
The warning, from Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, came as
thousands of Iraqi troops continued to mass near Kuwait's border.
In Kuwait City, residents formed queues at petrol stations, stocked up with
water and bought extra supplies from supermarkets. Banks reported unusually
heavy demand for dollars.
Kuwait has called up reservists and sent some 20,000 men - thought to be its
entire army - near its border with Iraq, and moved up 50 tanks.
Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said 'many squadrons' of F-15, F-16
and A-10 jets together with Awacs early-warning aircraft were being sent to
the region.
By late yesterday, 2,000 ship-borne marines had arrived in the Gulf and
4,000 more troops were due to arrive in Kuwait to operate tanks and armoured
personnel carriers positioned there after the 1991 Gulf war. Another 18,000
marines would begin moving to the region within days and about 14,000
infantry troops were also expected to be sent, a US defence offical said. In
addition, warships armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles were on their way to
the Gulf and the Red Sea.
Mr Christopher, in Jerusalem on the first leg of a Middle East peace
shuttle, said that Mr Saddam would be subjecting Iraq to 'devastation' if
his forces crossed into Kuwait.
'We're moving a lot of forces in there at the present time. It will be some
time, I think, before his forces are ready and we're in a very strong
deterrent mode.'
Mr Christopher said he would visit Kuwait during his week-long tour of the
region.
The US show of strength came amid reports that Iraq was deploying as many as
14,000 more troops and support armour towards the Kuwaiti border. US
officials said a 64,000-strong Iraqi force would soon be in place. Mr Hamed
Youssef Hammadi, Iraq's information minister, confirmed on Radio Monte Carlo
that Iraqi troops were within 20km of the Kuwaiti border - just 5km north of
the demilitarised zone straddling the border and policed by the
lightly-armed United Nations Iraq-Kuwait Observer Mission.
However, Iraq's intentions in massing troops north of Kuwait were no clearer
yesterday, although the state-run Baghdad Radio repeated threats that Iraq
would take unspecified 'measures' if the UN Security Council did not take
immediate steps to ease the four-year-old embargo on oil exports, which has
devastated the country's economy.
The commentary said Iraq had the 'right to take any measures' to defend
itself in the face of what it called 'an injustice of unprecedented
proportions' being inflicted by the UN, the US and Gulf neighbours.
Iraq appears to be attempting to force the hand of the Security Council
which will this week consider a report from Mr Rolf Ekeus, the UN envoy,
that comprehensive systems to monitor Iraq's chemical, nuclear, biological
and long-range missile manufacturing potential are ready to become
operational.
Iraqi officials have said that this means they are in compliance with UN
Gulf war ceasefire resolutions and sanctions should therefore be eased
immediately. Britain and the US have said they oppose setting any definite
criteria for lifting sanctions now. The US says Iraq has failed to comply
with the bulk of such resolutions and remains a regional threat. Iraq said
last night it was hoping for a diplomatic solution to the crisis, and
Russia, France and China - all permanent members of the Security Council -
were working on this.
In Kuwait City, the arrival offshore of a British frigate, HMS Cornwall,
provided a visible sign of US and British military support, an operation
that officials said would take several days to put fully in place.
