<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 94 / International Company News: Sell-off prompts INA changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Italian treasury last night carried out a management shake-up at INA,
the Italian insurance group, in advance of the final phase of the sell-off
the state's final 49 per cent tranche.
Using its powers as majority shareholder, the treasury has appointed 10 of
the 13 strong board as envisaged in INA's statutes prior to the sale in June
of the government's 51 per cent stake for L4,900bn. Mr Lorenzo Pallesi, the
chief executive who steered the privatisation road show, has been eased out
in spite of having been confirmed in his post five months ago when the
Berlusconi government took office.
The treasury said the new board had been composed in consultation with INA's
new shareholders. But not all the shareholders may be happy with the
reshuffle as there is an unwritten rule that managements do not change
during the course of privatisations. Two-thirds of the offering in June was
bought by North American and British institutions.
</TEXT>
