<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Analysts warn of provisions at Lucas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lucas Industries, the automotive and aerospace component maker, could make
provisions of up to Pounds 100m, pushing it into a headline loss when it
announces its annual figures on Monday.
The speculation among City analysts is that provisions could be at least
Pounds 17m to take into account costs involved in warding off litigation in
the US over lapses of quality control on aerospace component contracts with
the Defense Department.
But the provisions could reach as high as Pounds 100m, in the opinion of
Credit Lyonnais Laing, if Mr George Simpson, the new chief executive,
embarks on a major restructuring of the group to cut costs. This may involve
job losses and a continuation of the series of plant closures which go back
to 1991-92.
Lucas's difficulties in the US are well known, but any provisions for
restructuring remain guesswork until Mr Simpson, on Monday, outlines his
strategic plans for the group.
If the provisions go as far as the highest guess, then they would push Lucas
into a pre-tax loss. Without provisions, Lucas is expected to make pre-tax
profits of more than Pounds 65m, perhaps as much as Pounds 80m, for the year
to July, compared with Pounds 50.3m in 1992-93. The dividend is forecast to
stay at 7p.
Mr Simpson, since his arrival from Rover last April, has reviewed Lucas's
activities and concluded that the group should concentrate on aerospace and
automotive. The first priority, he has made clear, is to improve the group's
financial performance.
The plans, foreshadowed last week when Lucas put a software company up for
sale and said it was considering the sale of a manufacturing systems
consultancy, will also involve a new round of disposals. These are expected
largely to be companies in what was the group's applied technology division.
</TEXT>
