FT  08 OCT 94 / Letters to the Editor: Markets are not always right
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr STEPHEN BEER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I imagine Stephen Butler (Letters, October 3) has little practical
experience of financial markets, judging by his faith in them over central
bankers. Even casual observation - as opposed to simple economic theory -
leads to the conclusion that most market participants can be wrong for some
of the time.
Eventually they realise their mistake and the market corrects - often
dramatically.
Who I wonder, on average, is the most 'trustworthy' when predicting
inflation? Large numbers of traders with little option but to follow the
prevailing 'market view', or central bankers appointed by politicians but
with reputations to develop? Difficult one, that.
